descript.abstract: ESF Land Manager Jane Holte first mapped the watershed’s vegetation from aerial photography using manual interpretation methods in the late 1990s. The use of GIS technology was introduced during development of the Elkhorn Slough Watershed Conservation Plan in 1999, which included a detailed habitat map created by ESF in collaboration with Scharffenberger Land Planning and The Nature Conservancy. This manually interpreted map was updated using 2000-2001 aerial imagery and extensive field verification for publication in Elkhorn Slough at the Crossroads in 2002. In 2005, the map was further refined and converted to the newly adopted NERRS habitat classification standard. To support the Elkhorn Slough Early Mitigation Partnership, a watershed conservation strategy sponsored by the California Department of Transportation, the map’s boundaries were expanded using updated digitizing techniques in 2006. The current land cover map was produced through automated classification of June 2009 multispectral (4-band) NAIP orthoimagery.Please contact the Elkhorn Slough National Estuarine Research Reserve for additional information pertaining to this dataset.
